## CSS styling

CSS formatting can also be written in-line using the HTML style attribute to change the appearance of text.
For example, when indicating that a page is a work-in-progress, we add CSS to change the colour to highlight the message: `<span style="color:red">This page is a work in progress.</span>`.

CSS formatting should be used sparingly - only when it helps to communicate meaning - as some custom CSS could make the site less accessible.

The below table contains some examples of how styles can be used.

| Element | CSS | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- | 
| <span style="color:red">Red text</span> | `color:red` | --- | 
| <span style="background-color:yellow">Yellow background</span> | `background-color:yellow` | --- | 
| <span style="bgcolor="#28b463"">Green background</span> | `bgcolor="#28b463"` | --- | 